    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "That makes sense. I want to go deeper into the Locke/negative liberty angle. Specifically, I want to argue that because the internet is the modern 'public square', any state-mandated moderation or algorithmic oversight is essentially state-sponsored censorship. Can you expand on how the concept of 'natural rights' would support the idea that the state has zero legitimate authority to intervene in digital communication?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
